data.title: Fighting Illini Basketball Doubleheader Watch Party Set for State Farm Center
data.description: Gates will open at 6 p.m. CT and admission is FREE. Fans of all ages are encouraged to attend.
data.fulltext:
CLEAR BAG POLICY

CHAMPAIGN, Ill. – Fighting Illini Athletics will host a doubleheader basketball watch party at State Farm Center on Thursday, March 28 with both women's and men's basketball playing postseason games being shown on the videoboard. Gates will open at 6 p.m. CT and admission is FREE. Fans of all ages are encouraged to attend. 

The first 350 fans will get a free hot dog, courtesy of Illinois Student Affairs. Coca-Cola will be on site with giveaways and products for taste testing. Photo booth and giveaways also available from Max (formerly HBO). 

The women's basketball team begins its WBIT quarterfinal game at Tulsa at 6:30 p.m. CT, followed by the conclusion of the UConn/San Diego State men's game, and then the men's basketball Sweet 16 contest vs. Iowa State. In between games, there will be in-venue crowd participation contests like knockout, 3-point shooting, trivia and more. 

Concessions will be open with dinner options as well as drink specials -- $5 Twisted Tea, $3 Icon beer, $6 margaritas, and pink lemonades and $8 25oz Bud Lights. 

ENTRANCE AND PARKING: Fans should enter the West main gates of State Farm. Parking will be free in the northwest and southwest lots. The clear bag policy will be in effect.

data.title: Four Illini Named CSC Academic All-District
data.description: Kendall Bostic and Adalia McKenzie have earned their second honor of the sort in as many years while Genesis Bryant and Camille Hobby have been recognized for the first time.
data.fulltext:
CHAMPAIGN, Ill. – Four Illinois women's basketball student-athletes have been tabbed College Sports Communicators (CSC, formerly CoSIDA) Academic All-District honorees, the association announced on Tuesday.

Kendall Bostic and Adalia McKenzie have earned their second honor of the sort in as many years while Genesis Bryant and Camille Hobby have been recognized for the first time.

In her third season at Illinois, Bostic is in graduate school, working towards a master's degree in special education. Bostic earned her bachelor's degree from Illinois in speech and hearing sciences. McKenzie is also in her third season at Illinois, and is working towards an undergraduate degree in recreation, sport, and tourism. Bryant – a second-year Illini – is majoring in communication. A graduate transfer, Hobby earned her undergraduate degree from NC State in sport management and is working towards a master's degree in recreation, sport, and tourism at Illinois.

To be eligible for the award, nominees must have a 3.50 GPA and is at least a sophomore academically and athletically. Nominees must also be a starter or important reserve to the team and participated in at least 90 percent of the team's games or started 66 percent of contests.

On the court, Bostic is a double-double machine for the Illini, recording 14 on the season and 32 across her time at Illinois. The Kokomo, Indiana, native is averaging a double-double on the season with 12.3 points per game and 10.7 rebounds per game. Bostic has made 164 of her 268 field goal attempts on the season for a 61.2 field goal percentage. Bostic has tallied 50 assists, 35 steals, and 22 block on her senior campaign.

McKenzie has turned in an impressive junior campaign, averaging 11.2 points per game and 5.0 rebounds per game. The Brooklyn Park, Minnesota native is shooting at a 50.5 percent clip this season, making 140 of her 277 field goal attempts. She's tallied four double-doubles on the season to bring her career total to eight. McKenzie leads the team in offensive rebounds at 73 this year and has dished out 71 assists while swiping a team-beset 41 steals.

Bryant has settled in for the Orange and Blue and is averaging 13.8 points per game and 3.1 rebounds per game to go along with 101 assists (3.3/game). She delivered two 30-point games in the span of three contests to start her senior season. The Jonesboro, Georgia native has connected on 59 3-pointers this season and has racked up 39 steals.

Bostic, McKenzie, and Bryant have started all 31 games for Illinois this season.

Coming off the bench to start the season, Hobby worked her way into Illinois' starting lineup and has started 19 of the team's 31 games. The center is averaging 9.3 points per game to go along with 4.5 rebounds per game. Hobby recorded the first double-double of her career against Maryland on Feb. 11. The Jacksonville, Florida native scored a season-high 19 points on two occasions, both in Big Ten play.

Illinois is back in action in the WBIT quarterfinals on Thursday, March 28, when the team heads to [3] Tulsa.
